'Cangjie programming language_collection_Iterable_Collections_collection_iterable_equivalence': 'In Cangjie code language, A for-in loop in Cangjie can be translated into a while loop using the iterator and next methods. For example, the following for-in loop:
let list = [1, 2, 3]
for (i in list) {
    println(i)
}
}
is equivalent to the following while loop:

let list = [1, 2, 3]
var it = list.iterator()
while (true) {
    match (it.next()) {
        case Some(i) => println(i)
        case None => break
    }
}'

'Cangjie programming language_collection_Iterable_Collections_collection_iterable_interface': 'In Cangjie code language, The Iterable interface is an internal interface in Cangjie that supports iteration. It has the following core structure:
interface Iterable<T> {
    func iterator(): Iterator<T>
    ...
}
The iterator function returns an Iterator object, which is another internal interface.'

Code_Example:
interface Iterator<T> <: Iterable<T> {
    mut func next(): Option<T>
    ...
}

'Cangjie programming language_collection_Iterable_Collections_collection_iterable_while_let': 'In Cangjie code language, Another way to iterate over an Iterable is using the while-let syntax, which is a more concise form of the while loop. For example:
let list = [1, 2, 3]
var it = list.iterator()
while (let Some(i) <- it.next()) {
    println(i)
}'
